{{one source|date=May 2017}} {{use Oxford English|date=May 2017}} {{Infobox UN resolution |number = 181 |organ = SC |date = August 7 |year = 1963 |meeting = 1056 |code = S/5386 |document = https://undocs.org/S/RES/181(1963) |for = 9 |abstention = 2 |against = 0 |subject = Question relating to the policies of apartheid of the Government of the Republic of South Africa |result = Adopted |image = |caption = }}
{{International opposition to Apartheid}} '''[[United Nations]] [[List of UN Security Council Resolutions|Security Council Resolution]] 181''', adopted on August 7, 1963, was concerned with an arms build-up by the [[Republic of South Africa]] and fears that those arms might be used to further the racial conflict in that country. The Council called upon the government of South Africa to abandon its policy of [[apartheid]], as first requested to by [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 134|Resolution 134 (1960)]], and called upon all states to voluntarily cease the sale and shipment of all arms, ammunition and other military equipment to South Africa.
The resolution was adopted by nine votes to none; [[France]] and the [[United Kingdom]] [[Abstention|abstained]]. However, the resolution had little immediate effect on the conduct of the regime in South Africa.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hilaire|first=Max|title=United Nations law and the Security Council|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|date=2005|page=256|isbn=978-0-7546-4489-7}}</ref> {{UN-stub}} {{Apartheid-sa-stub}} ==See also== *[[List of United Nations Security Council Resolutions 101 to 200]] (1953 &ndash; 1965)
